    "instruction": "Load metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv, and error_logs.csv. For each of metric/trace/log files, aggregate by component (cmdb_id) and KPI name (use kpi_name for metric.csv, trace_name for trace.csv, log_name for log.csv). For each component-KPI compute: count, min, median (P50), P95, P99, and max using the full available series (do NOT filter by the incident window). Return a compact combined table with columns: source (metric/trace/log), cmdb_id, kpi_name, count, min, p50, p95, p99, max. Limit the returned rows to at most 50, sorted by count descending. Also return a short list of unique cmdb_id values found across all files and the total number of rows in each file. Do not perform any filtering by time window yet."
}

{
    "analysis": "From the previous aggregation step we confirmed metric.csv (1950 rows) and log.csv (450 rows) contain data; trace.csv and error_logs.csv are empty. Aggregation computed global statistics (including P95) per component-KPI across the full available series, which satisfies the requirement to calculate global thresholds before filtering. Next, per workflow we must extract data within the incident window and find anomalies by comparing incident-window points to the previously computed global thresholds. Traces and raw error logs are not available to help localize further, so metric and log anomalies will be primary evidence for fault identification.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv and log.csv, perform anomaly detection within the incident window 2024-01-19 15:42:56 to 2024-01-19 16:12:56 UTC as follows:\\n1) Recompute global P95 for every (source, cmdb_id, KPI) across the full available series (do NOT filter by time).\\n2) Filter each file to rows within the incident window (use pd.to_datetime(timestamp, unit='s', utc=True) and include endpoints).\\n3) For each (source, cmdb_id, KPI), mark incident-window rows as anomalies if value >= global_p95 (for both metric and log KPIs).\\n4) Produce a compact table (limit 20 rows) with columns: source, cmdb_id, kpi_name, global_p95, anomaly_count_in_window, earliest_anomaly_timestamp (UTC ISO), max_value_in_window, max_over_p95_ratio (max_value/global_p95 or null if global_p95==0). Sort by anomaly_count_in_window desc, then by max_over_p95_ratio desc.\\n5) Also return the count of rows in the incident window for metric.csv and log.csv (two numbers).\\nDo not print full time series; only return the compact table and the two incident-window row counts."
}

{
    "analysis": "The anomaly-detection step found many metric KPIs flagged as anomalous during the incident window, but two important caveats emerged: trace.csv and error_logs.csv are empty (so no trace-based localization), and many KPIs have global_p95 == 0 which makes the >=P95 rule produce meaningless alerts. A large group of socket-related KPIs across many services show anomaly_count_in_window = 25 and max_over_p95_ratio = 1.0 with earliest anomaly at 2024-01-19T15:45:00+00:00 — that indicates these series are at their historical P95 across the whole window, but not exceeding it by much. Because root-cause localization requires distinguishing true faults (significant deviations or consecutive breaches) from noise and zero-threshold artifacts, the next step is to narrow candidates to only those KPIs with meaningful thresholds (global_p95 > 0) and which exceed the P95 by a material amount (max_over_p95_ratio > 1). We also need to inspect temporal properties (earliest and latest anomaly timestamps) to see if any KPI shows a sustained consecutive breach that could be a fault. No trace data is available to disambiguate multiple service-level faults, so metrics and logs must provide the root cause. ",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From the previously computed global P95s and the incident-window flags, produce a compact list of metric/log KPIs that satisfy: global_p95 > 0 AND max_value_in_window / global_p95 > 1.0. For each matching (source, cmdb_id, kpi_name) return: source, cmdb_id, kpi_name, global_p95, anomaly_count_in_window, earliest_anomaly_timestamp (UTC ISO), latest_anomaly_timestamp (UTC ISO), max_value_in_window, max_over_p95_ratio. Limit to top 20 rows sorted by max_over_p95_ratio descending, then by anomaly_count_in_window desc. Also include the number of distinct (source, cmdb_id) components in this filtered set. Do not display full time series; just the compact table and the distinct-component count."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have identified multiple KPIs that exceeded their global P95 during the incident window. Key observations: orders.cpu shows the largest single max_over_p95_ratio (~2.08) but only 2 anomaly points; carts-db.log.row_count shows many anomaly points (24) spanning most of the window; shipping.socket shows many anomalies (16) across the window but with small ratio (~1.055). Many other KPIs have brief 1–2 point breaches or low absolute magnitudes (e.g., rabbitmq-exporter.cpu). Because traces are unavailable, we must use metrics/logs to identify true faults by finding consecutive anomaly runs (faults) rather than isolated spikes, and prefer faults that are sustained and show substantial deviation from threshold. The next step is to characterize consecutive anomaly runs for top candidate KPIs to determine which component has a sustained fault and which first occurrence likely represents the root cause.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "For the following candidate KPIs:\\n- metric.orders cpu\\n- log.carts-db log.row_count\\n- metric.shipping socket\\n- metric.queue-master diskio\\n- metric.user-db diskio\\n- metric.session-db diskio\\n- metric.rabbitmq-exporter cpu\\n- metric.carts workload\\nPerform fault-identification within the incident window 2024-01-19 15:42:56 to 2024-01-19 16:12:56 UTC as follows (use the previously computed global P95 per KPI):\\n1) Filter incident-window rows for each candidate.\\n2) Select rows where value >= global_p95 for that KPI.\\n3) Group those selected rows into consecutive runs where adjacent timestamps differ by exactly 60 seconds.\\n4) For each run, produce one row with: source, cmdb_id, kpi_name, run_start_timestamp (UTC ISO), run_end_timestamp (UTC ISO), run_length_points, max_value_in_run, max_over_p95_ratio (max_value_in_run/global_p95).\\n5) Limit output to top 20 runs sorted by run_length_points desc, then max_over_p95_ratio desc.\\nAlso return for each candidate: total_anomaly_points_in_window and number_of_runs. Keep outputs compact (no full raw time series)."
}

